st: the lighting of the paschal candle

r: In the darkness, fire is kindled; after which the Celebrant says
    tb: Dear friends in Christ: On this most holy night, in which our
    Lord Jesus passed over from death to life, the Church invites her
    members, dispersed throughout the world, to gather in vigil and
    prayer. For this is the Passover of the Lord, in which, by hearing
    his Word and celebrating his Sacraments, we share in his victory
    over death.

r: The Celebrant may say the following prayer
tb: Eternal God, who made this most holy night to shine with the
    brightness of your one true light: sanctify this new fire, we pray,
    and so set us aflame with the fire of your love, that with pure
    hearts and kindled affections we may attain to the radiance of
    your heavenly glory; through Jesus Christ our Lord. **Amen.**

r: If the Paschal Candle is to be marked, it is done at this time (Page 595).

pb:583
r: The Celebrant lights the Paschal Candle from the newly kindled fire, and says
r: May the light of Christ, rising in glory, banish all darkness from
    our hearts and minds.
r:The Deacon (or the Celebrant if there is no Deacon), bearing the Candle, leads the
    procession to the chancel, pausing three times and singing or saying
v: The light of Christ.
v:people: Thanks be to God.

r: If candles have been distributed to members of the Congregation, they are lit from
    the Paschal Candle. Other candles and lamps in the church, except for those at the
    Altar, may also be lit.
r: The Paschal Candle is placed in its stand.
r: Then the Deacon, or other person appointed, standing near the Candle,
    customarily sings or says the Exsultet.

st: the exsultet
l: Rejoice now, heavenly hosts and choirs of angels,
l: and let your trumpets shout Salvation
l: for the victory of our mighty King.
br:
l: Rejoice and sing now, all the round earth,
l: bright with a glorious splendor,
l: for darkness has been vanquished by our eternal King.
br:
l: Rejoice and be glad now, Mother Church,
l: and let your holy courts, in radiant light,
l: resound with the praises of your people.
br:
l: All you who stand near this marvelous and holy flame,
l: pray with me to God the Almighty
l: for the grace to sing the worthy praise of this great light;

pb:584
l: through Jesus Christ his Son our Lord,
l: who lives and reigns with him,
l: in the unity of the Holy Spirit,
l: one God, for ever and ever. **Amen.**

v:deacon: The Lord be with you.
v:people: And with your spirit.
v:deacon: Lift up your hearts.
v:people: We lift them up to the Lord.
v:deacon: Let us give thanks to the Lord our God.
v:people: It is right to give him thanks and praise.

tb: It is truly right and good, always and everywhere,
    with our whole heart and mind and voice to praise you,
    the invisible, almighty, and eternal God,
    and your only-begotten Son Jesus Christ our Lord;
    who paid for us the debt of Adam’s sin,
    and by his blood delivered your faithful people;
    for he is the true Paschal Lamb, the very Lamb of God,
    whose blood marks the doorposts of believers
    and makes us holy.
tb: This is the night when you brought our forebears,
    the children of Israel, out of bondage in Egypt,
    and led them through the Red Sea on dry land.
tb:o: This is the night when with a pillar of fire
    you banished the darkness of our iniquity.
tb: This is the night when all who believe in Christ
    are delivered from the gloom of sin,
    and are restored to grace and holiness of life.
tb: This is the night when Christ broke the bonds of death and hell,
    and rose victorious from the grave.

pb:585
tb:o: Our birth would have been no gain,
    had we not been redeemed.
tb: How wonderful and beyond our knowing, O God,
    is your mercy and loving kindness to us,
    that to redeem a slave, you gave a Son.
tb:o: O wonderful providence of Adam’s sin
    destroyed completely by the death of Christ.
    O happy fault, which gained for us
    so great and glorious a Redeemer.
tb: This is the night of which it is written:
    the night shall be as bright as the day.
tb: How holy is this night when wickedness is put to flight,
    and sin is washed away.
    It restores innocence to the fallen, and joy to those who mourn.
    It casts out pride and hatred, and brings peace and concord.
tb: How blessed is this night when earth and heaven are joined,
    and Man is reconciled to God.
tb: Therefore, O holy Father, accept our evening sacrifice,
    the offering of this candle in your honor,
tb:o: the work of bees and of your servants’ hands,
tb: the gift of your most holy Church.
    May it mingle with the lights of heaven,
    and shine continually to drive away all darkness.
    May Christ, the Morning Star who knows no setting,
    find it ever burning—he who gives his light to all creation,
    and who lives and reigns for ever and ever. **Amen.**

